</section>

<section class="tx-section">
  <h2>Why off-the-shelf ERPs fail textile mills</h2>
  <p class="sub">Generic ERPs are designed for discrete manufacturing — make a pump, ship a pump. Textile is a flow industry where one cotton bale becomes dozens of yarn cones, several beams, multiple dye lots, and finally finished garments. The data model is fundamentally different.</p>
  <p>A typical SAP B1 or Oracle NetSuite implementation assumes a deterministic bill of materials — 1 unit of raw material plus 1 unit of component yields 1 unit of output. Textile breaks this assumption at every stage. A 100 kg cotton bale produces 92 kg of carded sliver and 8 kg of soft waste. A spinning mill running 30s count today may switch to 40s tomorrow on the same ring frame, halving the production weight. A dye batch may yield 487 kg against a planned 500 kg because of shrinkage and shade rejection. Without lot-level traceability, costing becomes guesswork and rework is invisible.</p>
  <p>Tally migration is even harder. Tally is brilliant accounting software but it has no concept of a yarn count, a doff, a beam, a cut-order plan, or a sewing-line bundle. Mills that try to bolt textile workflow onto Tally end up with parallel Excel sheets that drift apart from the books within weeks. The reconciliation pain at year-end audit is one of the loudest reasons our textile customers come to us asking for a Tally alternative.</p>
  <p>Then there is the cluster reality. A Tirupur knitwear exporter sends 70 percent of work to third-party fabricators — knitting, dyeing, embroidery, printing, washing — each a separate job-work challan that must reconcile in/out quantities under GST section 143. A Coimbatore spinner runs three shifts on 50,000 spindles and needs spindle-level production capture to identify a slow-running frame. A Karur home-textile exporter must produce a packing list, certificate of origin, and LUT-based zero-rated export invoice in one click. <strong>None of these workflows are first-class in any imported ERP.</strong> They are built on top, painfully, by integrators who have never walked a mill floor.</p>
  <div class="tx-stat-row">
